Styling Requirements

Match Dynamics 365 native field styling — the input should look like it belongs in a model-driven form
Use Fluent UI v9 <Input>, <Textarea>, <Button>, <Tooltip> components
Use Fluent UI v9 design tokens for all colors (no hardcoded colors)
Icon buttons should use appearance="subtle" and match the native Dynamics icon style
The component must respect the form's read-only and disabled states:

Read-only: show value as text (no input), counter hidden, icon still clickable
Disabled: grayed out input, no interaction


Respect context.mode.isControlDisabled and context.mode.isVisible


Component Architecture
index.ts                 — PCF lifecycle (init, updateView, destroy)
EnhancedTextField.tsx    — Main React component
EnhancedText.tsx     — Counter sub-component
FieldIcon.tsx            — Icon button sub-component (phone/email/url)
types.ts                 — Interfaces and types
utils.ts                 — Validation helpers, field type detection
Data Flow
index.ts
  ├── reads metadata (MaxLength, Type) from context.parameters.value.attributes
  ├── reads current value from context.parameters.value.raw
  ├── passes props to EnhancedTextField.tsx
  └── calls context.parameters.value.raw = newValue (via notifyOutputChanged)

EnhancedTextField.tsx
  ├── manages local input state
  ├── renders input/textarea based on field type
  ├── renders EnhancedText with current/max
  ├── renders FieldIcon based on field type
  └── calls onChange callback → index.ts → notifyOutputChanged
Key Implementation Notes

getOutputs() must return the value:

typescriptpublic getOutputs(): IOutputs {
  return { value: this.currentValue };
}

Respect PCF lifecycle — don't call notifyOutputChanged() during updateView(). Only call it from user-initiated events (onChange).
Use context.parameters.value.raw (not .formatted) to get/set the actual value.
Auto-resize textarea for Multiple fields — calculate height based on content using a hidden measurement element or scrollHeight.
Focus/blur handling — match Dynamics behavior where the field shows the full edit UI on focus, and a compact display on blur.


